00:43:50,294 --> 00:43:53,058
What in the world is wrong
with George?

716
00:43:53,230 --> 00:43:56,131
Trying to be like his dad, Bush.

717
00:43:56,300 --> 00:43:59,064
He got us out here
for nothing whatsoever.

718
00:43:59,236 --> 00:44:02,501
I am so furious right now, Mama.

719
00:44:03,240 --> 00:44:08,371
I really hope they do not
re-elect that fool, honestly.

720
00:44:08,546 --> 00:44:11,344
I am in good spirits,
and I am doing okay.

721
00:44:11,515 --> 00:44:13,278
I really miss you guys.

722
00:44:13,451 --> 00:44:15,419
Thanks for the Bible...

723
00:44:17,088 --> 00:44:19,716
...and books and candy.

724
00:44:19,890 --> 00:44:24,020
I really look forward to letters
from you guys.

725
00:44:24,195 --> 00:44:28,427
Well, tell all the family hello
and that I am doing fine.

726
00:44:28,599 --> 00:44:32,035
We don't expect anything
to happen any time soon.

727
00:44:32,203 --> 00:44:36,401
I cannot wait to get home
and get back to my life.

728
00:44:36,574 --> 00:44:38,701
Tell Sputnik congrats...

729
00:44:38,876 --> 00:44:42,539
...and I'll see my first nephew soon...

730
00:44:43,314 --> 00:44:45,578
...as soon as I get back
to the States.

731
00:44:46,183 --> 00:44:48,276
Hope you guys are doing okay...

732
00:44:48,452 --> 00:44:50,443
...and keep sending the mail.

733
00:44:50,621 --> 00:44:53,954
It makes getting through
the days easier.

734
00:44:56,560 --> 00:44:59,495
Well, I am on my way to bed...

735
00:44:59,664 --> 00:45:03,156
...so I will write you guys soon.

736
00:45:03,334 --> 00:45:05,461
I love and miss...

737
00:45:05,636 --> 00:45:07,763
...all of you guys."

738
00:45:20,384 --> 00:45:22,716
I want him to be alive...

739
00:45:22,887 --> 00:45:25,685
...and I can't make him alive.

740
00:45:26,757 --> 00:45:29,624
But your flesh just aches.

741
00:45:29,794 --> 00:45:32,285
You want your child.
It's out of sync.

742
00:45:32,463 --> 00:45:36,365
A parent is not supposed
to bury their child.

743
00:45:39,103 --> 00:45:43,039
I feel... I feel sad for my family...

744
00:45:43,207 --> 00:45:45,539
...because we lost our son.

745
00:45:46,911 --> 00:45:48,606
But...

746
00:45:48,779 --> 00:45:51,942
...I really feel sorry
for the other families...

747
00:45:52,116 --> 00:45:57,179
...that is losing their kids
as we speak.

748
00:45:59,423 --> 00:46:01,288
And for what?

749
00:46:01,459 --> 00:46:03,256
L... I don't...

750
00:46:04,395 --> 00:46:07,455
That's the...
I guess the sickening part.

751
00:46:07,631 --> 00:46:08,928
For what?

752
00:46:09,333 --> 00:46:11,460
You've heard a lot
about Halliburton lately.

753
00:46:13,070 --> 00:46:16,597
Criticism is okay. We can take it.
Criticism is not failure.

754
00:46:16,774 --> 00:46:18,901
Our employees are doing
a great job.

755
00:46:19,076 --> 00:46:22,136
We're feeding the soldiers.
We're rebuilding Iraq.

756
00:46:22,313 --> 00:46:25,510
Will things go wrong?
Sure they will. It's a war zone.

757
00:46:25,683 --> 00:46:28,151
We're serving the troops
because of what we know...

758
00:46:28,319 --> 00:46:29,786
...not who we know.

759
00:46:29,954 --> 00:46:33,014
Let me tell you about Halliburton,
the company I ran.

760
00:46:34,625 --> 00:46:36,456
I'm proud of what I did at Halliburton.

761
00:46:36,627 --> 00:46:39,790
The people are proud of what
they've accomplished. I, frankly...

762
00:46:39,964 --> 00:46:41,932
...don't feel any need to apologize...

763
00:46:42,099 --> 00:46:45,000
...for the way I've spent my time
over the last five years...

764
00:46:45,169 --> 00:46:47,899
...as the CEO and chairman
of a major American corporation.

765
00:46:48,072 --> 00:46:50,768
This is also an attempt
to divert attention...

766
00:46:50,941 --> 00:46:54,035
...from the fact they have
no energy policy.

767
00:46:54,211 --> 00:46:57,510
And as the secretary of energy said,
"We were caught unawares."

768
00:46:59,750 --> 00:47:04,278
In the middle of the war, Microsoft,
DHL and other corporations...

769
00:47:04,455 --> 00:47:06,616
...invited Halliburton
to a conference...

770
00:47:06,791 --> 00:47:10,591
...to figure out how much money
could be made in Iraq.

771
00:47:11,695 --> 00:47:13,526
Having worked this...

772
00:47:15,633 --> 00:47:19,831
...effort, even since before the...
The invasion...

773
00:47:20,004 --> 00:47:22,666
...the liberation of Iraq started.

774
00:47:22,840 --> 00:47:27,675
You, industry, are definitely
a vital part of that effort.

775
00:47:27,845 --> 00:47:30,905
We appreciate your interest
in this. We need you.

776
00:47:31,081 --> 00:47:33,242
Lots of you are small businesses
and struggling:

777
00:47:34,952 --> 00:47:37,750
"How do we get a piece of this?
You big guys are gonna get it.

778
00:47:37,922 --> 00:47:41,414
The rest of us will have subcontracting
capability or none at all."

779
00:47:41,592 --> 00:47:43,856
USTDA is for you.

780
00:47:44,028 --> 00:47:45,791
Once that oil starts flowing...

781
00:47:45,963 --> 00:47:48,022
...and money coming,
gonna be lots of money.

782
00:47:48,199 --> 00:47:50,599
It's the second-largest
reserve of oil in the world.

783
00:47:50,768 --> 00:47:52,497
No question of how much
money's there.

784
00:47:52,670 --> 00:47:55,639
I've been getting complaints
from Iraqi firms and American firms.

785
00:47:58,142 --> 00:48:00,201
The lack of transparency,
the corruption.

786
00:48:00,377 --> 00:48:05,076
I think the profits American companies
are making, the main companies...

787
00:48:05,249 --> 00:48:06,511
...are so overwhelming.

788
00:48:06,684 --> 00:48:10,142
I mean, when you have a line item
for a million dollars...

789
00:48:10,321 --> 00:48:13,518
...and you subcontract it out
for 50 or 60 or $70,000...

790
00:48:13,691 --> 00:48:14,953
...that's a huge profit.

791
00:48:15,125 --> 00:48:17,525
It's the American taxpayer
that's gonna pay for that.

792
00:48:17,695 --> 00:48:21,062
And it's gonna get better.
Start building relationships.

793
00:48:21,232 --> 00:48:23,063
Because it's gonna get
much better...

794
00:48:23,234 --> 00:48:25,634
...as the oil flows
and their budgets increase.

795
00:48:25,803 --> 00:48:28,636
Good news is, whatever it costs,
the government will pay you.

796
00:48:28,806 --> 00:48:31,639
War is always good
for certain companies...

797
00:48:31,809 --> 00:48:34,039
...that are in the war...
The business of war.

798
00:48:36,814 --> 00:48:38,372
We're very proud.

799
00:48:40,050 --> 00:48:41,847
Supporting U.S. Government
and military.

800
00:48:42,019 --> 00:48:44,613
The real heroes of the campaign
and the reconstruction...

801
00:48:44,788 --> 00:48:47,154
...are the men and women
of the U.S. Armed Forces.

802
00:48:47,324 --> 00:48:49,884
We're proud of being any part
we can in supporting them.

803
00:48:50,060 --> 00:48:54,087
Halliburton delivers hot meals,
supplies, clean clothing...

804
00:48:54,265 --> 00:48:56,756
...and communications
to our soldiers...

805
00:48:56,934 --> 00:49:01,166
...so they can be
a little closer to home.

806
00:49:02,506 --> 00:49:03,973
It's a girl!

807
00:49:04,141 --> 00:49:07,133
Halliburton. Proud to serve
our troops.

808
00:49:07,311 --> 00:49:10,712
I just read in the paper
Halliburton got another contract.

809
00:49:10,881 --> 00:49:13,782
- Halliburton got another contract.
- That's right.

810
00:49:13,951 --> 00:49:16,545
Which is not being...

811
00:49:17,788 --> 00:49:19,119
...contested at all.

812
00:49:19,290 --> 00:49:20,689
Because nobody knows.

813
00:49:20,858 --> 00:49:23,418
Well, it's in the paper,
so somebody knows.

814
00:49:23,594 --> 00:49:27,655
But that's after it happens,
after the fact. It's too late.

815
00:49:28,632 --> 00:49:32,762
The United States is now a major
player in the Iraqi oil business.

816
00:49:32,937 --> 00:49:35,030
American troops
guard the oil fields...

817
00:49:35,205 --> 00:49:38,299
...as Texas oil workers
assess their potential.

818
00:49:38,475 --> 00:49:42,036
It's a safe environment to work in.
We don't feel any risk.

819
00:49:42,212 --> 00:49:45,147
We feel we're being well protected
here, or we wouldn't be here.

820
00:49:45,316 --> 00:49:46,578
It's no secret. I mean...

821
00:49:46,750 --> 00:49:50,880
...I make anywhere between
2 and 3000 a month.

822
00:49:51,055 --> 00:49:53,285
A Halliburton employee
out here driving a bus...

823
00:49:53,457 --> 00:49:56,824
...can make between 8 and 10,000
a month. Explain that one to me.

824
00:49:56,994 --> 00:49:58,484
For 40 hours a week.

825
00:49:58,662 --> 00:50:00,721
Driving the same
two-and-half-mile route.

826
00:50:00,898 --> 00:50:02,229
Go figure.

827
00:50:02,399 --> 00:50:04,492
Where's the justification in that?

828
00:50:04,668 --> 00:50:07,603
There's no other single area
of the world today...

829
00:50:09,306 --> 00:50:11,706
...with the opportunity
for business, new business...

830
00:50:11,875 --> 00:50:14,844
...similar to the opportunity
that's available today in Iraq.

831
00:50:15,012 --> 00:50:16,809
The president went in,
did what he did.

832
00:50:18,415 --> 00:50:20,007
We're supporting him
and our troops.

833
00:50:20,184 --> 00:50:24,780
We wanna make sure
that the efforts and the lost lives...

834
00:50:24,955 --> 00:50:26,422
...wasn't for no reason.

835
00:50:26,590 --> 00:50:29,024
If it wasn't for the oil,
nobody would be there.

836
00:50:29,193 --> 00:50:30,854
Nobody would worry about it.

837
00:50:31,028 --> 00:50:33,053
Unfortunately,
at least for the near term...

838
00:50:34,999 --> 00:50:38,025
...we think it's gonna be a good
situation, a dangerous situation.

839
00:50:38,202 --> 00:50:40,762
Good for business,
bad for the people.

840
00:50:40,938 --> 00:50:44,396
Today on the news,
Rumsfeld was saying...

841
00:50:44,575 --> 00:50:48,511
And Wolfowitz was saying:

842
00:50:48,679 --> 00:50:52,206
"The Iraqi people are much,
much better off.

843
00:50:52,383 --> 00:50:55,477
Isn't it better that we
got rid of Saddam...

844
00:50:55,652 --> 00:50:59,418
...and now the Iraqi people
can do what they wanna do...

845
00:50:59,590 --> 00:51:01,649
...and really be free?"

846
00:51:01,825 --> 00:51:04,692
Will they ever be free?
No, they'll not be free.

847
00:51:04,862 --> 00:51:07,831
And where are the weapons
of mass destruction?

848
00:51:07,998 --> 00:51:10,933
It was a... We were duped.
We were really duped.

849
00:51:11,101 --> 00:51:12,568
And these poor people...

850
00:51:12,736 --> 00:51:15,967
...the young men and women
who are being killed there.

851
00:51:16,140 --> 00:51:17,869
- It's unnecessary.
- That's a disgrace.

852
00:51:18,042 --> 00:51:20,306
- That's it. No more.
- That's a disgrace.

853
00:51:20,477 --> 00:51:24,106
They died in a just cause,
for defending freedom...

854
00:51:24,281 --> 00:51:27,409
...and they will not
have died in vain.

855
00:51:38,629 --> 00:51:41,962
Lila had called to tell me
she was coming down from Flint...

856
00:51:42,132 --> 00:51:45,966
...to Washington, D. C.
To attend a jobs conference.

857
00:51:46,370 --> 00:51:48,736
On her break, she said
she was going to go...

858
00:51:48,906 --> 00:51:51,932
...and pay a visit
to the White House.

859
00:51:58,949 --> 00:52:02,180
Bush killed children. Iraqi children.

860
00:52:02,352 --> 00:52:06,220
- My son, killed.
- Killed my people in Spain, yesterday.

861
00:52:06,390 --> 00:52:10,053
- Lies kill people. Your children too.
- Yes, my son.

862
00:52:10,227 --> 00:52:12,923
They have no business to do
in Iraq now. They're killing...

863
00:52:13,097 --> 00:52:14,689
...all these young Americans.
- Yes.

864
00:52:14,865 --> 00:52:18,528
For what? For oil.
Bush is a terrorist.

865
00:52:18,702 --> 00:52:21,068
- No, he isn't. This is all staged.
- Yes, he is.

866
00:52:21,238 --> 00:52:23,433
- This is all staged.
- My son.

867
00:52:23,607 --> 00:52:27,475
- Where was he killed?
- You tell me my son is not a stage.

868
00:52:27,644 --> 00:52:29,976
- Where was he killed?
- He was killed in Karbala.

869
00:52:31,648 --> 00:52:35,880
April 2nd. It's not a stage.
My son is dead.

870
00:52:36,053 --> 00:52:38,647
There are a lot of other people too.

871
00:52:42,626 --> 00:52:44,651
Blame al Qaeda.

872
00:52:48,398 --> 00:52:50,332
What did that woman yell at you?

873
00:52:50,501 --> 00:52:53,732
That I'm supposed
to blame the al Qaeda.

874
00:52:53,904 --> 00:52:58,466
The al Qaeda didn't make a decision
to send my son to Iraq.

875
00:52:59,510 --> 00:53:03,037
Ignorance that we deal with,
with everyday people.

876
00:53:03,213 --> 00:53:05,511
Because they don't know.
People think they know...

877
00:53:05,682 --> 00:53:09,709
...but you don't know.
I thought I knew, but I didn't know.

878
00:53:14,791 --> 00:53:17,419
I need my son.

879
00:53:35,078 --> 00:53:37,603
God, it's tougher than I thought
it was gonna be...

880
00:53:37,781 --> 00:53:39,646
...to be here.

881
00:53:40,484 --> 00:53:42,247
But it's freeing also...

882
00:53:42,419 --> 00:53:44,284
...because I finally have a place...

883
00:53:44,454 --> 00:53:47,981
...to put all my pain
and all my anger...

884
00:53:48,158 --> 00:53:50,251
...and to release it.

885
00:53:55,732 --> 00:53:59,793
I guess I was tired of seeing people
like Lila Lipscomb suffer.

886
00:53:59,970 --> 00:54:04,430
Especially when, out of
the 535 members of Congress...

887
00:54:04,608 --> 00:54:08,066
...only one had an enlisted son
in Iraq.

888
00:54:11,215 --> 00:54:14,116
I asked Corporal Henderson of
the United States Marine Corps...

889
00:54:14,284 --> 00:54:16,149
...to join me on Capitol Hill...

890
00:54:16,320 --> 00:54:19,517
...to see how many members
of Congress we could convince...

891
00:54:19,690 --> 00:54:22,659
...to enlist their children
